Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing airline on-time preformance from about 2.5 million flights spanning from 1987 to 2008 (with the exception of the years 2001 & 2002).

DataType Issues¶

  • WeatherDelay & NASDelay were stored originally as strings for ease of merging datasets -- but need to convert to floats.

Data Issues¶

  • 1 Origin destination is from "D", origin codes are supposed to be 3 letters, not one -- will fix entry to be a NULL entry
  • "PA (1)" is a Unique carrier. Looked strange at first, but this is actually a common naming convention when there are multiple carriers with the same two letter abbreviation.
  • Negative & 0 DepDelay. For the analysis I'd like to conduct, I only want positive departure delay times. Need to remove these entries fom the dataframe.
  • 80% of the data is missing for in the specific delay types. This information is important for my analysis, so I will be removing those rows. I will still be left with ~487703 entries.

Data Structure Issues¶

  • Extra Column "Unnamed" - delete. Seems to be an extra index column.
  • Would like to have a delay type column.

# replace entries with NaN
def entry_to_nan(df, column, entry):
    """ This function will replace specific entries in a column and replace them with NaN.
    Remember that NaN means - not a number.
    ---------------
    Parameters:
    df - should be the name of the dataframe
    column - the name of the column with the entries you want to replace. PUT IN QUOTES!
    entry - the entries that you want to replace with NaN. *Put in quotes if its a string.
    """
    indices = df[df[column] == entry].index
    df.loc[indices, column] = float('nan')
In [105]:
# replace entries with None
def entry_to_none(df, column, entry):
    """ This function will replace specific entries in a column and replace them with None.
    Remember that None is used for an empty cell for a string datatype.
    ---------------
    Parameters:
    df - should be the name of the dataframe
    column - the name of the column with the entries you want to replace. PUT IN QUOTES!
    entry - the entries that you want to replace with None. Put in quotes if it's a string!
    """
    indices = df[df[column] == entry].index
    df.loc[indices, column] = None

Issue #5¶

Add delay type column.

Code¶
In [122]:
def type_list(df, col, letter):
    '''This function goes row-by-row through a column. If the entry is 0.0 adds "None" to the list, 
    if the entry is non-zero, it adds a specified letter to the list.'''    
    col_list = []
    for x in range(df.shape[0]):
        if df[col].iloc[x] == 0.0:
            col_list.append("None")
        else:
            col_list.append(letter)
    return(col_list)
In [123]:
def consolidate_delay_type(row):
    """
    Reads df row by row & consolidates
    'carrier','weather', 'nas', 'security', 'late'
    into one column. 
    """
    cols = ['carrier','weather', 'nas', 'security', 'late']
    if len(set(row[col] for col in cols)) == 1:
        return "None"
    else:
        return ", ".join([row[col] for col in cols if row[col] != "None"])

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 200,802 flights logged in the dataset with 25 features.

Most of the features are numeric, but there are a few categorical features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in figuring out what features are best for predicting how long the departure of flight will be delayed (DepDelay).

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the following features will help provide insight on how long a flight will be delayed:

Quantitative:

  • DepDelay
  • CarrierDelay
  • WeatherDelay
  • NASDelay
  • SecurityDelay
  • LateAircraftDelay

Qualitative:

  • DayOfWeek
  • UniqueCarrier
  • Origin & Dest
  • Delay

What is the distribution of delay times for each delay type?¶

In [9]:
# make histplot function
def nonzero_hist(df, col, x_label, bins):
    '''This function will plot a histogram for the non-zero entries in 
    column of interest with a specified x_label, and specified number of bins.
    ---------------
    Parameters:
    df - the dataframe of interest
    col - the column of interest (PUT IN QUOTES)
    x_label - the string to use for the x-axis label (PUT IN QUOTES)
    bins = the number of bins to use'''
    
    #pull non-zero entries from column of interest
    data = df[df[col] != 0]
    #plot histogram of column of interest
    plt.hist(data = data, x = col, bins = bins, color = 'blue');
    plt.xlabel(x_label);

All of the delay time variables are right-skewed with long tails suggesting strong outliers on the right. I will be looking at these outliers to see if they need to be filtered out of the data.

From the distrubtion charts above, it looks like:

  • CarrierDelay and LateAircraftDelay have the largest ranges in time delays, followed by WeatherDelay and NASDelay.
  • Security delay has the smallest range in delay times.
  • Security delay is also the only data doesn't have a significant drop after just the first bin.

Overall it looks like it's not as common for delays to be long. Even at 100 minutes, there are relatively few in each delay type compared to the more frequent bins.

In [16]:
# create function for plotting each delay type with a log transformation
def log_delaytype(df, col, log_bins, title):
    '''This function will plot a histogram for the non-zero entries in a
    specific delay type column using a log scale.
    ---------------
    Parameters:
    df - the dataframe of interest
    col - the column of interest (PUT IN QUOTES)
    log_bins - the size of the log bins to use (best to keep between 0.05 & 0.2)
    title - the string to use for the historgram title (PUT IN QUOTES)'''
    
    #setting up bins
    log_binsize = log_bins
    bins = 10 ** np.arange(0, np.log10(df[col].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)
    
    #pull non-zero entries from column of interest
    data = df[df[col] != 0]
    
    #plotting histogram
    plt.hist(data = df, x = col, bins = bins, color = 'blue');
    plt.xscale('log');
    plt.xticks([1e0, .333e1, 1e1, 3e1, 1e2, 3e2, 1e3], [1, 3, 10, 30, 100, 300, 1000])
    plt.xlabel('Delay Time (in minutes)');
    plt.title(title);

In [21]:

Interestingly enough, after applying a log transformation to each delay type, they all appear uni-modal with the following peaks:

  • Carrier Delay: 3-40 minutes
  • Weather Delay: 10-50 minutes
  • NAS Delay: 3-40 minutes
  • Secuity Delay: 5-25 minutes
  • Late Aircraft Delay: 9-80 minutes

I also think it's interesting that all the delay type peaks start at around similar times at or below 10 minutes. I also find it interesting that none of the upper bounds go above 100 minutes.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The delay times took on a long-tail right skew, so I performed a log transform. Under the distribution the data looks roughly multi-modal with one peak between 1-2, another peak from 4-6, and a final peak from 10-20.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I needed to perform a log transform on the times for each delay type (as I did with the general delay time). I found it interesting that they were all roughly uni-modal and had peaks with similar lower bounds (all at or below 10). I also found it interesting that none of the peaks had upper bounds greater than 100.

As far as adjusting the data, I did consider cutting out outlier delay time data. I ultimately decided not to because the outliers weren't due to miscoding & the large delay times could have useful information.

Conclusions¶

At the beginning of this project, I had started with about 2.5 million flights spanning from 1987 to 2008. After wrangling the data, dealing with missing values, and only keeping data with flight delays, I was left with about 200K flights. Although only a fraction of what I started with, it still felt like an exceptable amount of data to do some analysis. Note: after wrangling there were only 4 remaining airline carriers.

Throughout my exploration, the main feature of interest has been departure delay time. Here is what I found:

Features with high frequency of departures delays:

  • Late Aircraft delays, Carrier Delay, and NAS (National Aviation System) delays
  • WN (Southwest Airlines) had the most delayed flights out of all 4 carriers
  • The top 10 origins and destinations for delayed flights were: LAS, PHX, PHL, MDW, CLT, BWI, ORD, LAX, OAK, & HOU
  • Most of the days of the week had about the same frequency except for Saturday (1/3 less than the day with the highest frequency).

Features that contribute to short departure delays (less than 40 minutes):

  • WN and US (carriers):
    • In general, US Airways (US) has the smallest IQR for departure delay times.
    • Southwest (WN) and US Airways (US) tend to have lower average delay times (20-32 minutes)
  • Security and NAS delays:
    • On any given day of the week, the average departure delay time for Security delays and NAS delays are between 25-40 minutes.
    • There was one exception for Security on Saturdays, but considering these features have low frequencies, I wouldn't trust that data point as a generalization.

Features that contribute to long departure delays (above 40 minutes):

  • Weather delays: From day to day, the average delay times are around 60-90 minutes.
  • Late Aircraft & Carrier delays:
    • The correlation between Late Aircraft delays above 80 minutes and Departure Delay was 0.93. The correlation between Carrier delays above 80 minutes and Departure Delay was 0.91.
    • From day to day, the average delay times are around 50-60 minutes.
  • XE & UA (carriers):
    • In general, JSX Airline (XE) & United Airlines (UA) have a lot of spread in their upper quartiles for departures delay times, spreading up to 100 minutes.
    • From day to day, the average delay times are around 35 - 50 minutes (with the exception of Saturday and Sunday).
  • Common Airports:
    • The most common airports have significantly more high outlier delay times than the less common airports.
    • ORD (Chicago O'Hare International Airport) has the longest average delay time over any other airport for every day of the week, 35-60 minutes.

Interesting finds:

  • US Airways (US) and Southwest Airlines (WN) have the lowest NAS delays on average (around 20-25 minutes)
  • US Airways (US) have the longest security delays on average at about 80 minutes.
